# While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,color = 'orange') if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2,color='tab:cyan') # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='purple', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.

def perc_on_bar(z):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''

    total = len(data[z]) # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    ax = sns.countplot(data[z],palette='Paired')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

### Function to plot stacked bar charts for categorical columns
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set()
    ## crosstab 
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x,data['Attrition_Flag'],margins=True).sort_values(by=1,ascending=False)
    print(tab1)
    print('-'*120)
    ## visualising the cross tab
    tab = pd.crosstab(x,data['Attrition_Flag'],normalize='index').sort_values(by=1,ascending=False)
    tab.plot(kind='bar',stacked=True,figsize=(17,7))
    plt.legend(loc='lower left', frameon=False)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions and Boxplots of enrollees
def plot(x,target='Attrition_Flag'):
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(12,10))
    axs[0, 0].set_title('Distribution of Attrited Customer')
    sns.distplot(data[(data[target] == 1)][x],ax=axs[0,0],color='teal')
    axs[0, 1].set_title('Distribution of Existing Customer')
    sns.distplot(data[(data[target] == 0)][x],ax=axs[0,1],color='orange')
    axs[1,0].set_title('Boxplot w.r.t Attrition_Flag')
    sns.boxplot(data[target],data[x],ax=axs[1,0],palette='gist_rainbow')
    axs[1,1].set_title('Boxplot w.r.t Attrition_Flag - Without outliers')
    sns.boxplot(data[target],data[x],ax=axs[1,1],showfliers=False,palette='gist_rainbow')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

  • Lets impute the rows with income_category,Education_Level,Marital_Status
  • We will use KNN imputer to impute missing values.
  • KNNImputer: Each sample's missing values are imputed by looking at the n_neighbors nearest neighbors found in the training set. Default value for n_neighbors=5.
  • KNN imputer replaces missing values using the average of k nearest non-missing feature values.
  • Nearest points are found based on euclidean distance.
  • We need to first convert Unknown to NaN

Building the model¶

Model evaluation criterion:¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer will leave credit card services while they will not - False positives or Type 1 error
  2. Predicting a customer will not leave credit card services while they will - False negatives or Type 2 error

Which case is more important?¶

  • Predicting a customer will leave but in real if they dont leave doesnt cause any loss of revenue to company. However predicting a customer will not leave but in reality if they leave will cause loss of revenue. So Type 2 error should be less.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?¶

  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall lesser the chances of false negatives.
In [644]:
##  Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall and Precision
def get_metrics_score(model,train,test,train_y,test_y,flag=True):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    score_list=[] 
    
    pred_train = model.predict(train)
    pred_test = model.predict(test)
    
    train_acc = model.score(train,train_y)
    test_acc = model.score(test,test_y)
    
    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    score_list.extend((train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision))
        
    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True: 
        print("Accuracy on training set : ",model.score(train,train_y))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ",model.score(test,test_y))
        print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(train_y,pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(test_y,pred_test))
        print("Precision on training set : ",metrics.precision_score(train_y,pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ",metrics.precision_score(test_y,pred_test))
    
    return score_list # returning the list with train and test scores
In [645]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

    j = get_metrics_score(model,X_train_un,X_test,y_train_un,y_test,False)
    acc_train.append(j[0])
    acc_test.append(j[1])
    recall_train.append(j[2])
    recall_test.append(j[3])
    precision_train.append(j[4])
    precision_test.append(j[5])

Decision Tree with pipeline and Grid search hyperparameter tuning¶

In [679]:
from sklearn import decomposition, datasets
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

#Staring the timer
start_time = timeit.default_timer()

std_slc = StandardScaler()
pca = decomposition.PCA()
dec_tree = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()

#Pipeline will helps us by passing modules one by one through GridSearchCV for which we want to get the best parameters.
#So we are making an object pipe to create a pipeline for all the three objects std_scl, pca and dec_tree
pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('std_slc', std_slc),
                           ('pca', pca),
                           ('dec_tree', dec_tree)])
#StandardScaler doesnt need any parameters
#Principal Component Analysis requires a parameter 'n_components' to be optimised
n_components = list(range(1,5))
#DecisionTreeClassifier requires two parameters 'criterion' and 'max_depth' to be optimised
criterion = ['gini', 'entropy']
max_depth = [2,4,6]

parameters = dict(pca__n_components=n_components,
                      dec_tree__criterion=criterion,
                      dec_tree__max_depth=max_depth)

#Making an object for GridSearchCV and fitting the dataset i.e X and y

dtreePipeGSrch = GridSearchCV(pipe, parameters)
dtreePipeGSrch.fit(X_train,y_train)

#stopping the timer and appending to the array to comapre across models
elapsed = timeit.default_timer() - start_time
print(elapsed)
elapsed_arr.append(round(elapsed,3))

Comparing all the Ensemble models with Randomized/Grid searches and also without either¶

In [703]:
# defining list of models
models = [dtree,rf_estimator,bagging_estimator,abc,gbc,xgb,dtreePipeGSrch,randomForestPipeGSrch,baggingPipeGSrch,
          abcPipeGSrch,gbcPipeGSrch,xgbPipeGSrch,          dtreePipeRandSrch,randomForestPipeRandSrch,
          baggingPipeRandSrch,abcPipeRandSrch,gbcPipeRandSrch,xgbPipeRandSrch]

# defining empty lists to add train and test results
search_type=[]
acc_train = []
acc_test = []
recall_train = []
recall_test = []
precision_train = []
precision_test = []

# looping through all the models to get the accuracy, recall and precision scores
for model in models:
    j = get_metrics_score(model,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test,False)
    if model in(dtree,rf_estimator,bagging_estimator,abc,gbc,xgb):
        search_type.append('')
    elif model in (dtreePipeGSrch,randomForestPipeGSrch,baggingPipeGSrch,abcPipeGSrch,gbcPipeGSrch,xgbPipeGSrch):
        search_type.append('Grid')
    else:
        search_type.append('Randomized')
    acc_train.append(np.round(j[0],2))
    acc_test.append(np.round(j[1],2))
    recall_train.append(np.round(j[2],2))
    recall_test.append(np.round(j[3],2))
    precision_train.append(np.round(j[4],2))
    precision_test.append(np.round(j[5],2))

  • XGBoost has highest Accuracy and 2nd highest Recall and precision
  • Gradient Boost has highest accuracy and recall
  • Random Forest has highest Precision
  • Bagging has 2nd highest Accuracy and precision
  • Decision is lowest on all the 3 parameters
  • Bagging and gradient boost have 1 on many training parameters suggesting its overfit
  • Overall performance of all the 3 parameters are better for all the boosting methods as compared to the non boosting ones

  • XGBoost has highest Test accuracy and Recall
  • Gradient Boost and Random Forest has highest Precision
  • Gradient Boost has also highest accuracy and 2nd highest recall
  • XGBoost has also 3rd highest precision
  • Bagging has 2nd highest precision
  • Decision Tree has lowest Accuracy, recall and precision
  • Bagging and XG boost have 1 on many training parameters suggesting its overfit
  • Overall performance of all the 3 parameters are better for all the boosting methods as compared to the non boosting ones

Comparison between Grid and Random search¶

  • First of all want to mention that I had to run grid search with only a few values in list for parameters as if I had put it would never end and keep on executing for ever. So the comparison of times between both are not apples to apples
  • We can see that execution times of both the types of searches are almost same with differences only in 2nd decimal place,accross all the models
  • Randomizedsearch is taking almost equal time with more number of values in the list. So definetly Random is faster than Grid
  • I would definetly recommmend use of Randomized search over Grid because its way much faster and almost equal in terms of performance metrices

Actionable Insights & Recommendations¶

  • Attrition percentage is higher in older people so more preference should be given to older people like lower interest rates etc
  • Higher attrition is seen on people having low relationship count. So that could be indicator that a person is trying to leave thats why engaging less with bank
  • All the people with Contacts counts =6(max) left the bank. Thats a good indicator that someone who is contacting more has some complaints thats why they are trying to contact more. We need better customer care for listening to customer complaints
  • Customer age mean is towards the lower side which says that younger people are using credit cards more
  • Utiilization ratio is very low. We need to encourage users to use cards more instead of cash by various schemes like cash back etc
  • Platinum seems to have highest attrition. Maybe something is wrong with that card_category like interest rate or something. needs to be investigated
